```ts viiv-gateway-api/src/app.module.ts:22-31
// Excerpt from: class AppController
@Controller()
class AppController {
  @Get()
  getHello() {
    // const apiVersion = process.env.APP_VERSION || 'unknown';
    return {
      version: process.env.npm_package_version,
    };
  }
}
```
Add current timestap to this return value
```ts
@Get()
getHello(): object {
  const timestamp = new Date().toISOString();
  return {
    version: process.env.npm_package_version,
    timestamp,
  };
}
```

This will include the current timestamp in ISO format (e.g., "2022-03-14T15:47:26.829Z") along with the `version` property in the returned object.
Ok, but current date should be gtm-3 (brazil)
```ts
@Get()
getHello(): object {
  const timestamp = new Date().toLocaleString('pt-BR', { timeZone: 'America/Sao_Paulo' });
  return {
    version: process.env.npm_package_version,
    timestamp,
  };
}
```

This will format the current date and time in Brazil's GTM-3 timezone (Sao Paulo) using the `toLocaleString` method with appropriate locale ('pt-BR') and timezone ('America/Sao_Paulo').
Keep it an ISO string
 ```ts
@Get()
getHello(): object {
  const timestamp = new Date().toISOString().replace('Z', 'America/Sao_Paulo');
  return {
    version: process.env.npm_package_version,
    timestamp,
  };
}
```

This will convert the current date and time to an ISO string with the GTM-3 timezone offset (`America/Sao_Paulo`).
That is not returning the sao paulo local time
 ```ts
import { parseISO } from 'date-fns';

@Get()
getHello(): object {
  const now = new Date().toISOString();
  const timestamp = parseISO(now).toLocaleString('pt-BR', { timeZone: 'America/Sao_Paulo' });
  return {
    version: process.env.npm_package_version,
    timestamp,
  };
}
```

Using `date-fns`'s `parseISO` function to ensure the correct timezone conversion.
